1 Introduction

In this document, we show the missing data model fit for the glucodensities on the 580 AEGIS-I subjects at baseline. As there are a total of 1516 subjects, once we fitted the model, we imputed the glucodensities on the remaining 936 subjects. All glucodensities (actual and imputed) will subsequently be used for the estimation of diabetes incidence as well as diabetes survival.

2 Details of Covariates

A total of 1516 individuals were chosen for our analyses with Continuous Glucose Monitoring (CGM) available for 580 individuals between 1 and 5 days. The covariates used in the models include sociodemographic and clinical variables such as Age, Body Mass Index (BMI, \(kg/m^2\)), glycated haemoglobin (HbA1c, %), baseline Fasting Plasma Glucose (FPG, \(mmol/L\)), Insuline, and Albumin, along with the categorical variables Sex, Smoking habits and presence or absence of Diabetes melitus (\(DM\)). Age at the baseline moment (AEGIS-I) was in the range 18 to 91 years. Overall, there are 183 (12.07%) of individuals with \(DM\) at baseline.

To understand the distribution of the covariates between the levels of the Sex variable, we constructed Table 2.1.

3 Glucodensities estimation at baseline (AEGIS I). Imputation of missing responses using inverse probably weighting estimator

In this Section, we are going to fit the missing data model using the baseline information from the 1516 subjects in the AEGIS-I study. The variables we want to use are âAgeâ, âSexâ, âHbA1câ, âFPGâ, âSmokingâ habits, âAlbuminâ, and âBMIâ.

3.1 Computing the weights

As a first step, we are going to assign a â0â to the subjects without continuous glucose monitoring (CGM) and a â1â with CGM. In Table 3.1, the proportion of subjects without and with CGM at baseline is shown.

cgm <- round(prop.table(table(data1_id$cgm)), 3)
Table 3.1: Proportion of subjects with CGM in AEGIS-I.
CGM Proportion
0 = No 0.617
1 = Yes 0.383

Second, we are going to estimate the probability of non being missing, as a function of Age, Sex, HbA1c, FPG, Smoking habits, Albumin, and BMI. For that, we fit a logistic GAM regression model (Wood 2017).

mod <- gam(cgm ~ s(Age) + Sex + s(HbA1c) + s(FPG) + Smoking + s(Albumin) + s(BMI), data = data1_id, family = binomial)
summary(mod)

The fit of this model is not very good (deviance explained = 10.14%, adjusted \(R^2\) = 0.11). Even so, this indicates that we are dealing with a MNAR data process. In Figure3.1, the effect of the covariates is depicted. From the Figure, it can be seen that from about 65 years of age onwards, participation in the CGM study decline sharply and almost linearly. In contrast, this probability is higher for very high values of HbA1c and in women.

plot(mod, pages = 1, scale = 0, all.terms = T)

Figure 3.1: Smooth effect of âAgeâ, âHbA1câ, âFPGâ, âAlbuminâ, âBMIâ, âSexâ, and âSmokingâ on the probability of having GCM.

We then calculated the inverse weights for each subject by taking those with no CGM measurements to 0, and considering the inverse of the fitted values obtained with the previous model and normalizing them for those subjects with CGM measurements.

data1_id$weights <- as.numeric(as.character(data1_id$cgm))/mod$fitted.values
data1_id$weights <- data1_id$weights/sum(data1_id$weights)

weight = data1_id$weights

In Figure 3.2 we show the histogram of the weights for the individuals with CGM measurements, indicating in blue its mean value, NA.

ggplot(data1_id[data1_id$cgm == 1,], aes(x = weights)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "lightgrey") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "Weights", y = "Count") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean(weights)), color="blue",linetype = "dashed")

Figure 3.2: Histogram of the weights for the individuals with CGM measurements. Vertical blue dashed line indicates the mean value, NA.

3.2 Computing the quantiles of the glucodensities

For computing the glucodensities, we will create a grid with 300 equally-spaced points (âQgridâ) and compute the quantiles of the CGM at each point for each subject. Those without CGMs will be assigned a vector of 0. We save the glucodensities in a matrix called âQinâ.

py = 50 # Length of the grid
Qgrid = seq(0, 1, length = py)
ny = dim(data1_id)[1] # Number of individuals
Qin = matrix(0, ncol = py, nrow = ny)
for(i in 1:ny){
  if(data1_id$cgm[i] == 1){
    Qin[i, ] <- quantile(data1$Glucose[data1$ID == data1_id$ID[i]], probs = Qgrid)
  }
}
rm(i)

3.3 Selecting the explanatory variables

At this point we have to select the explanatory variables, creating a training data set (âxinâ) and a test data set (âxoutâ), which should be data.frames. In this case, the training and the test databases are going to be the same, and we will include all subjects for the both of them and only the covariates we are interested in (âAgeâ, âSexâ, âHbA1câ, âFPGâ, âSmokingâ, âAlbuminâ, and âBMIâ). Since we have two categorical covariates (âSmokingâ and âSexâ), we need to use their corresponding dummy variables.

data1_id$tab1 <- ifelse(data1_id$Smoking == "Ex-smoker", 1, 0)
data1_id$tab2 <- ifelse(data1_id$Smoking == "Smoker", 1, 0)

xin = xout = data1_id[, c("Age", "sex", "HbA1c", "FPG", "tab1", "tab2", "Albumin", "BMI")]
px = ncol(xin)

3.4 Fitting the missing data model

Now that we have computed the weights and the quantiles of the glucodensities and selected the variables, we proceed to fit the model.

m = GloWassRegfinal(xin = xin, Qin = Qin, xout = xout, weight = weight, Qgrid = Qgrid, Rsquared = T)

The model fitted has a \(R^2\) = 0.63, and the estimated coefficients of the model are shown in Figure 3.3.

beta = matrix(0, nrow = px + 1, ncol = py)

xout_s <- as.matrix(xout)
for(i in 1:py){
  maux =  lm(Qin[, i] ~ xout_s[, 1] + xout_s[, 2] + xout_s[, 3] + xout_s[, 4] + xout_s[, 5] + xout_s[, 6] + xout_s[, 7] + xout_s[, 8], 
             weights = weight)
  beta[, i] = maux$coefficients
}

betas <- cbind(t(beta), Qgrid)

par(mfrow = c(3, 3))

4 Using actual and estimated glucodensities from AEGIS-I for the estimation of diabetes incidence (AEGIS-II)

In this Section, we use the quantiles of the glucodensities from AEGIS-I (580 real glucodensities and 936 estimated ones using the weighted linear regression model) in the estimation of the incidence of diabetes.

First of all, we are going to keep only those individuals without diabetes in AEGIS-I, a total of 1333 subjects (87.93% of the sample). Second, we are going to eliminate those individuals with a follow up of less than 6 months (or 0.5 years), a total of 40 subjects, so now we have a total of 1293 individuals.

cgm_est$cgm  <- as.numeric(as.character(cgm_est$cgm))

4.4 Calibration and accuracy measurements of the complete model

In this section, we are performing calibration measurements to the model with fPCAs and the other covariates, since it seems to be the best performing model. In Figure 4.8 we show the calibration plot of the model, together with different calibration and discrimination measurements.

inc <- mean(data1_id$Incidence)

val.prob(data1_id$fitted_pca, data1_id$dm_incidence)

##           Dxy       C (ROC)            R2             D      D:Chi-sq 
##   0.844988893   0.922494446   0.466055854   0.184737184 239.865178499 
##           D:p             U      U:Chi-sq           U:p             Q

To evaluate the overall performance of the model, one of the most commonly used measures is Nagelkerkeâs \(R^2\). This measure severely penalizes false predictions close to 0, which abound in our model due to the low predicted probabilities. With this in mind, an \(R^2\) = 0.477 is a good value. An alternative to \(R^2\) is the Somersâ \(D_{xy}\) rank correlation index (Somers 1962), which ranges from -1 (very poor model performance) to 1 (very good performance). In our case, \(D_{xy}\) = 0.853, indicating an excellent model fit.

Another of the most common overall performance measures is the Brier score, which is not easy to interpret, as it depends on the incidence of the disease. Because of this, we calculate the scaled Brier score, which takes values between 0 and 1, and the closer to 1, the better the model discriminates. The incidence in this sample is 0.058, which leads us to the maximum Brier score of 0.055. In this case, the scaled Brier score is 0.369. However, in our case it does not give us much information, since it is based on the difference between the predicted probability and the actual value (0 or 1), and the mean of the predicted probability for the cases is just 0.366, and the cutoff point for the probability is 0.055, which is very small.

In Figure 4.8 we can see that up to a predicted probability of approximately 0.055, the model calibration is perfect; from 0.055 to approximately 0.2 of predicted probability, as well as from approximately 0.65 onwards, the model seems to overestimate (i.e.Â the predicted probability is higher than the actual probability); on the other hand, between a predicted probability of 0.2 and 0.65, the model underestimates, i.e.Â it predicts a probability lower than the actual probability. Looking at the Harrel E-statistics, it can be seen that these deviations are very small (the mean of the absolute deviations, Eavg = 0.009, while the maximum of the absolute deviations Emax = 0.082). Siguiendo con las medidas de calibraciÃ³n, lo ideal es que el intercepto de calibraciÃ³n (tambiÃ©n conocido como calibration-in-the-large) sea 0, asÃ­ como que la pendiente de calibraciÃ³n sea 1. En nuestro caso, Intercept = 0.097 y Slope = 1.057, que son muy prÃ³ximos a estas cifras ideales. El unreliability index U (also known as recalibration index), testea la desviaciÃ³n de estos dos Ã­ndices de sus valores ideales a la vez, obteniÃ©ndose un p-valor = 0.839, es decir, esta desviaciÃ³n no es estadÃ­sticamente significativa. All this leads us to affirm that the calibration of the model is very good.

In terms of discrimination, the most commonly used index is the C-index, which in logistic models coincides with the AUC, which has already been discussed above, and the discriminative capacity of the model was found to be outstanding.

All this leads us to the conclusion that the chosen model presents a very good overall performance. For more information on these measures, we urge the reader to consult Steyerberg (2009).

5 Using actual and estimated glucodensities from AEGIS-I for the incidence of diabetes (AEGIS-II). Testing the adequacy of estimates according to conformal inference confidence bands

In this Section, we perform the missing data model fit for the quantiles of the glucodensities on the 580 AEGIS-I subjects at baseline to imput the glucodensities on the remaining 936 subjects. Then, we use the use these quantiles functions from AEGIS-I in the estimation of the incidence of diabetes.

The novelty here with respect to what we did in the previous Section is that we will use one part of the sample for the estimation of the quantiles of the glucodensities and the other part for the calculation of the confidence bands for this estimation. Once the bands are obtained, we will keep only those imputations whose maximum radius of the bands is smaller than the given radius. In doing so, we aim to eliminate estimates with higher uncertainty, as they are perceived as less âreliableâ. We will test with different radii to try to obtain an optimal cut-off point for this radius, measured in terms of the AUC over time of the survival models where we will use these imputations, as well as their corresponding C index. The incidence model chosen is inci_pca), since it was proven to be the best model for estimate the incidence of diabetes.

5.1 Fitting the missing data model

The process is very similar to the one in the previous Section, using the same individuals, the same covariates and the same weights. As we already mentioned, in this case we use a third of the sample with known CGM for the estimation of the quantiles of the glucodensities and the other two thirds for the estimation of 95% confidence bands, using conformal inference.

colnames(Qin) = paste("Q", 1:py, sep = "")
data1_comp$Q = Qin

dat0 <- data1_comp[data1_comp$cgm == 0, ] # The ones we want to imput
dat1 <- data1_comp[data1_comp$cgm == 1, ] # Train dataset
set.seed(123)
m <- concurrentconformal(formula = "Q ~ Age + sex + HbA1c + FPG + tab1 + tab2 + BMI + Albumin", prob = 0.95, xpred = dat0, var_weights = weights, data = dat1, plot = F)
radio <- (m$upper - m$lower)/2
radio <- apply(radio, 1, max)
data1_comp$radio <- 0
data1_comp$radio[data1_id$cgm == 0] <- radio

Now, we consider only the individuals with no diabetes in AEGIS-I, and also with a followup time larger than 6 months (half a year).

data1_id <- merge(data1_id, data1_comp[, c("ID", "radio", "Q")], by = "ID", all.x = T)

Below, we show the summary for the maximum radios, with a balanced separation or the training set.

summary(data1_id$radio[data1_id$cgm == 0])
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     0.0     0.0   131.3   112.8   199.4   609.5

5.3 Fitting the longitudinal models and computing the time-dependent AUCs and the C index

n <- length(grid_radios)

nsample <- numeric(n)
times <- vector(mode = 'list', length = n)

C <- numeric(n)

for(i in 1:n){
  dat <- data1_id[data1_id$radio <= grid_radios[i], ]
  nsample[i] <- dim(dat)[1]
  
  ### Computing the PCAs
  gluco <- fdata(dat$Q, argvals = Qgrid, names = list(main = "Glucodensities", xlab = "Prob", ylab = "Glucose levels"))
  ##' Computing the fPCA
  res.pc <- fdata2pc(gluco, ncomp = 3)
  pc3est <- res.pc$rotation # Estimated PCA
  dat$PC1 <- res.pc$x[, 1]
  dat$PC2 <- res.pc$x[, 2]
  dat$PC3 <- res.pc$x[, 3]
  
  log_pca <- gam(Incidence ~ Sex + s(Age) + s(BMI) + s(HbA1c) + s(Insuline) + s(PC1) + s(PC2) + s(PC3), data = dat, family = "binomial")
  dat$fitted_pca <- log_pca$fitted.values
  oc_pca <- optimal.cutpoints("fitted_pca", status = "Incidence", method = "SpEqualSe", data = dat, tag.healthy = 0)
  
  C[i] <- as.numeric(substr(summary(oc_pca)$p.table$Global$AUC_CI, 0, 5))
 
  AUC[[i]] <- roc(dat$Incidence, log_pca$linear.predictors, ci = TRUE, ci.type = "shape")
}

6 Using actual and estimated glucodensities from AEGIS-I for the survival free of diabetes (AEGIS-II)

In this Section, we go a step further and take the follow-up time into account, to estimate the probability free of diabetes using survival models. To do so, we are sticking only to the 1293 individuals without diabetes which also have a follow-up time of more than half a year.

6.1 Survival models for the risk of diabetes

In this section, we are going to estimate the risk of diabetes over time as a function of the functional principal components (fPCA) of the glucodensities, adjusting or not for other covariates, using an additive Cox regression model.

6.1.1 Using fPCA for the glucodensities as only covariates

6.2 Comparing the three models in terms of AUC over time

In this subsection we are comparing the three models to see the differences in discrimination between all of them. For this, we are going to use de AUC curve over time. In Figure 6.4 we can see the AUC curves over time for the three models.

auc1 <- risksetAUC(data1_id$followup, status = data1_id$Incidence, tmax = 10, marker = cox_pca_simple$linear.predictors,
                   xlab = "Follow up time (years)", main = "")
par(new = TRUE)
auc2 <- risksetAUC(data1_id$followup, status = data1_id$Incidence, tmax = 10, marker = cox$linear.predictors,
                   col = 2, xlab = " ")
par(new = TRUE)
auc3 <- risksetAUC(data1_id$followup, status = data1_id$Incidence, tmax = 10, marker = cox_pca$linear.predictors,
                   col = 3, xlab = " ")

legend("topright", legend = c("Only fPCAs", "Only baseline covariates", "fPCAs and baseline covariates"), lwd = 1, 
       col = c(1, 2, 3), cex = 0.8)

Figure 6.4: AUC curves for the three survival models considered.

We can see differences between the AUC curves for the three models, but are these differences statistically significant? For answering this question, we are going to stick to the models with and without fPCAs, but always considering other baseline covariates, since they were the ones with higher AUCs over time, and compute the difference between the two curves. To assess whether this difference is significant, we calculated by bootstrap, using 1000 samples, the 95% confidence interval of the difference in AUCs. As can be seen in the Figure 6.5, this interval does not contain 0, which means that the full model has a statistically significantly higher AUC than the model containing only the non-functional variables.

auc <- auc3$AUC - auc2$AUC

B = 1000
AUC <- matrix(rep(0, l = length(auc)*B), nrow = B)
set.seed(12345)
for(l in 1:B){
  data.a <- bootstrap.sample(data1_id)
    mod.a <- gam(followup ~ Sex + s(Age) + s(BMI) + s(HbA1c) + s(Insuline), data = data.a, family = cox.ph(), weights = Incidence)

  mod.b <- gam(followup ~ Sex + s(Age) + s(BMI) + s(HbA1c) + s(Insuline) + s(PC1) + s(PC2) + s(PC3), data = data.a, family = cox.ph(), weights = dm_incidence)
  
  data.a$eta1 <- mod.a$linear.predictors
  data.a$eta2 <- mod.b$linear.predictors
  #
  out1 <- risksetAUC(data.a$followup, status = data.a$Incidence, marker = data.a$eta1, tmax = 10,
                     plot = F, predict.time = 0.5)
  #
  out2 <- risksetAUC(data.a$followup, status = data.a$Incidence, marker = data.a$eta2, tmax = 10,
                     plot = F, predict.time = 0.5)
  #
  difauc <- out2$AUC - out1$AUC
  for(k in 1:length(auc2$utimes)){
    AUC[l, k] <- interpolate(out2$utimes, difauc, auc2$utimes[k])
  }
}

ci <- apply(AUC, 2, quantile, probs = c(0.025, 0.975))

plot(auc2$utimes, auc, lwd = 2, type = "l", ylim = c(-0.3, 0.3), main = "", 
     xlab = "Follow up time (years)", ylab = "AUC difference", xlim = c(0, 10))
par(new = TRUE)
plot(auc2$utimes, ci[1, ],lwd = 1, lty = 2, type = "l", ylab = "", xlab = "", 
     ylim = c(-0.3, 0.3), xlim = c(0, 10), col = 'darkgray')
par(new = TRUE)
plot(auc2$utimes, ci[2, ], lwd = 1, lty = 2, type = "l", ylab = "", xlab = "", 
     ylim = c(-0.3, 0.3), xlim = c(0, 10), col = 'darkgray')

cord.x <- c(auc2$utimes, auc2$utimes[length(auc2$utimes):1])
cord.y <- c(ci[1, 1:length(auc2$utimes)], ci[2,length(auc2$utimes):1])
polygon(cord.x, cord.y, col = 'darkgray', border = "darkgray")
abline(h = 0, lty = "dashed")
lines(auc2$utimes, auc, lwd = 2, type = "l", xlim = c(0, 10))

Figure 6.5: Difference of AUC over time of the full model with respect to the model without functional covariates. The 95% confidence interval calculated by bootstrap resampling with 1000 samples is shown in grey.

C index for the chosen model was 0.817.

7 Using actual and estimated glucodensities from AEGIS-I for the survival free of diabetes (AEGIS-II). Testing the adequacy of estimates according to conformal confidence bands

In this Section, we perform the same analysis as for the incidence, but for estimating the survival free of diabetes. Therefore, we use the same intervals for radius.

7.1 Fitting the survival model for different radios

In this Section we are going to fit the complete survival model from the previous Section including only those imputed values whose confidence bands have a maximum radius equal or less than a given radius, from a grid of radii. This grid is the same that we used on previous analysis.

n <- length(grid_radios)

nsample <- numeric(n)
times <- vector(mode = 'list', length = n)
AUC <- vector(mode = 'list', length = n)
C <- numeric(n)

for(i in 1:n){
  dat <- data1_id[data1_id$radio <= grid_radios[i], ]
  nsample[i] <- dim(dat)[1]
  
  ### Computing the PCAs
  gluco <- fdata(dat$Q, argvals = Qgrid, names = list(main = "Glucodensities", xlab = "Prob", ylab = "Glucose levels"))
  ##' Computing the fPCA
  res.pc <- fdata2pc(gluco, ncomp = 3)
  pc3est <- res.pc$rotation # Estimated PCA
  dat$PC1 <- res.pc$x[, 1]
  dat$PC2 <- res.pc$x[, 2]
  dat$PC3 <- res.pc$x[, 3]
  
  cox_pca <- gam(followup ~ Sex + s(Age) + s(BMI) + s(HbA1c) + s(Insuline) + s(PC1) + s(PC2) + s(PC3), data = dat, family = cox.ph(), weights = Incidence)
